# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: angela-stachowa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:angela-stachowa/angela-stachowa] Stachowa was born in Prague on 16 August 1948, the daughter of the Sorbian writer Jurij Měrćink.
[src:angela-stachowa/angela-stachowa] After graduating from Sorbische Oberschule in Bautzen in 1967, she studied at TU Dresden, graduating in 1972 with a degree in engineering economics, specializing in electrical engineering/electronics.
[src:angela-stachowa/angela-stachowa] From 1973 to 1976, she was a research assistant at Karl-Marx-Universität Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/angela-stachowa] For her work she received the Domowina art prize, the Art Prize of the City of Leipzig (1986) and the OIRT radio play prize, as well as the Johann Gottfried Herder Medal in gold.
[src:angela-stachowa/angela-stachowa] Some of her works have been translated into Czech, Polish, Russian, Swedish, Croatian and English.
[src:angela-stachowa/angela-stachowa] Stachowa was a member of the SED from 1972 to 1989.
[src:angela-stachowa/angela-stachowa] From 20 December 1990 to 10 November 1994, she was a member of the German Bundestag for one term.
[src:angela-stachowa/angela-stachowa] She was elected to parliament as a non-party member for the PDS/Left List via the Land list Saxony into parliament.
[src:angela-stachowa/angela-stachowa] During the legislative period, she resigned from the PDS parliamentary group on 15 June 1994, but retained her mandate as a non-party member.
[src:angela-stachowa/angela-stachowa] She died there on 29 March 2022 at the age of 73.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The town lies in the hilly Upper Lusatian Gefilde (*Hornjołužiske hona*), a part of the northwesternmost foothills of the Sudetes, just north of the Lusatian Highlands.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Elbe→ North Sea), and the Bautzen Reservoir (*Budyska rěčna zawěra*) lies in the north of the town.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In 2021, Bautzen had a population of around 38,000.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Although Görlitz is larger, it is Bautzen that is regarded as the historical capital of Upper Lusatia.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Bautzen is the political and cultural center of the entirety of the Slavic minority of the Sorbs (Upper and Lower), although Lower Lusatia and the Lower Sorbian-speaking Sorbs have their own, second center, which is Cottbus.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] About 10 percent of Bautzen's population is Upper Sorbian-speaking.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The use of the language is more widespread in the countryside surrounding the town than in the town itself.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Bautzen is the seat of several Sorbian institutions like the Domowina, the German-Sorbian People's Theater (*Němsko-Serbske ludowe dźiwadło*), and Sorbian Broadcasting (*Sorbischer Rundfunk*, *Serbski rozhłós*).
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] From 1346 until 1815, the town was a member of the Lusatian League.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The Bautzen Wenceslaus' Market (*Bautzener Wenzelsmarkt*, Upper Sorbian: *Budyske Wjacławske wiki*) is "Germany's oldest Christmas market mentioned in a chronicle".
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Asteroid *11580 Bautzen* is named in honour of the city.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Like other cities and places in Lusatia, Bautzen has several different names across languages.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Its German name was also officially changed in 1868.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The town on the River Spree is situated about 50 km (31 mi) east of Dresden between the Lusatian highland and the lowlands in the north, amidst the region of Upper Lusatia.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] To the north stretches the Bautzen Reservoir, which was flooded in 1974.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] This is the former location of the villages of Malsitz (*Małšecy*) and Nimschütz (*Hněwsecy*).
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The old part of Bautzen is located on the plateau above the Spree, whose top is marked by the Ortenburg castle.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The later-built more recent quarters in the east were enclosed by the city ramparts.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] After their removal, the city expanded further east and to the left bank of the river.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] However, there has only been a small urban area west of the Spree until today.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In the 1970s, the development areas of "Gesundbrunnen" and "Allendeviertel" were erected.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] After 1990, several neighbouring villages were incorporated.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The city is bordered by Radibor, Großdubrau and Malschwitz in the North, Kubschütz in the East, Großpostwitz, Obergurig and Doberschau-Gaußig in the South, as well as Göda in the West.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] All of these belong to the Bautzen district.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In the 3rd century AD an eastern Germanic settlement existed here, but excavations have proved that the region was already inhabited as early as the late Stone Age.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Sorbs arrived in the area during the migration period in the 6th century AD.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The first written evidence of the city is from 1002 under the name *Budusin* (Upper Sorbian: *Budyšin*, Polish: *Budziszyn*).
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In 1018 the Peace of Bautzen was signed between the German king Henry II and the Polish ruler Bolesław I the Brave.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The treaty left the town under Polish rule.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In 1032 it passed to the Margraviate of Meissen within the Holy Roman Empire, in 1075 to the Duchy of Bohemia, elevated to a kingdom in 1198 (with short periods of Brandenburgian and Hungarian rule).
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In 1346, Budissin became a member of the Lusatian League, an alliance of Upper Lusatian cities, also including Görlitz, Kamenz, Lauban, Löbau and Zittau.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In 1429 and 1431, it was unsuccessfully besieged by the Hussites.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In 1547, the town was subjected to the Upper Lusatian Pönfall, a punitive measure imposed by Ferdinand I in his capacity as King of Bohemia after political disobedience during the Schmalkaldic War, which resulted in the loss of self-governing privileges.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In 1634, it was destroyed by the Swedes during the Thirty Years' War.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In 1635, Budissin fell to the Electorate of Saxony, whose Prince-electors were also Polish kings in personal union from 1697 to 1763.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] One of two main routes connecting Warsaw and Dresden ran through the town at that time.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] During the Napoleonic Wars, it was the site of the Battle of Bautzen (1813).
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In 1868, the name was officially changed from *Budissin* to the more Germanized form *Bautzen*.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In 1839, the Sorbian student organization **Societas Slavica Budissenensis** was founded in the city.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In 1845, the Sorbian national anthem was publicly performed for the first time in the city.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The *Sorbian House* (Upper Sorbian: *Serbski Dom*), a Sorbian cultural centre, was opened in the city in 1904.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] After the Nazi Party came to power in Germany in 1933, many political prisoners were held in the Bautzen I and Bautzen II prisons, built in 1904 and 1906, respectively.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] During the *Kristallnacht* in 1938, local Jews were persecuted and Jewish-owned businesses were destroyed.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] During World War II, in 1942–1943, the Nazis conducted three trials of members of the Polish resistance at the local court, sentencing thirteen to death.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The *AL Bautzen* subcamp of the Groß-Rosen concentration camp operated in Bautzen.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] At least 600 men, mostly Poles, but also of other nationalities, were imprisoned there, about 310 of whom died.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Ernst Thälmann was imprisoned there before being deported to Buchenwald.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In April 1945, the Germans evacuated many prisoners on foot to Nixdorf, where they were liberated by Polish troops on May 8, 1945, while the remaining prisoners were liberated in Bautzen by the Soviets on April 20, 1945.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Between 21 April and 30 April 1945, the Battle of Bautzen was fought which resulted in the town being recaptured by the German army.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] This meant Bautzen and its surroundings stayed in German hands until Germany's capitulation.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] From 1952 to 1990, Bautzen was part of the Bezirk Dresden of East Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Bautzen was infamous throughout East Germany for its two penitentiaries.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] "Bautzen I" was used as an official prison, soon to be nicknamed **Gelbes Elend** ("Yellow Misery") due to its outer colour, whereas the more secretive "Bautzen II" was used as a facility to hold political prisoners, dissidents and prisoners of conscience.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Today, Bautzen I is known as the Bautzen Correctional Institution and is used to hold prisoners who are awaiting trial.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Bautzen II which was also operated by the GDR's Ministry for State Security, has served as an open memorial since 1993, operated by the Saxon Memorials Foundation.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Guided tours are provided and occasionally, films are screened.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] A permanent exhibition depicts the misery suffered by occupants; visitors may tour detention cells, the isolation area and the yards where prisoners were allowed to exercise.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] In 2002 the city commemorated its 1000th birthday.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] During the Early Middle Ages, Bautzen was one of the largest cities in Central Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] However, from around the 15th century, its population growth began to stagnate.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The relatively late onset of industrialization in Bautzen brought new momentum, leading to population growth even during the era of East Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Following the Peaceful Revolution of 1990, however, the city’s population declined significantly, dropping from 52,000 in 1989 to around 38,000, largely due to emigration and low birth rates.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Since the early 2000s, this decline has slowed considerably.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Today, Bautzen ranks as the 10th largest city in Saxony by population.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] As of December 31, 2011, 98.3% of Bautzen's residents were of German origin, with 6.1% having a migration background.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The Bautzen City Council consists of 34 members.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] It meets either in the Town Hall or in the Gewandhaus.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] There are also four local councils (Niederkaina, Stiebitz, Kleinwelka, and Salzenforst-Bolbritz), whose honorary members are elected for five years.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Bautzen has a very compact and well-preserved medieval town centre with numerous churches and towers and a city wall on the steep embankment to the river Spree, with one of the oldest preserved waterworks in central Europe (built 1558).
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] There are six museums in Bautzen, including the Stadtmuseum Bautzen ("Bautzen city Museum"), the Sorbisches Museum ("Sorbian Museum", Sorbian: *Serbski muzej*) and the Senfmuseum (*Mustard Museum*).
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] Alstom Transportation operates a large factory on Fabrikstraße making railway locomotives, carriages and trams.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] It was built by the former VEB Waggonbau Bautzen, which was acquired by Bombardier Transportation in 1998 via Deutsche Waggonbau and acquired by Alstom when Bombardier Transportation was sold by parent Bombardier Inc. in 2021.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] The mustard *Bautz'ner Senf* is produced in Bautzen.
[src:angela-stachowa/bautzen] It is the market leader in the new states of Germany with a market share of 65 percent.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The **Bundestag** (German: [ˈbʊndəstaːk] ⓘ, 'Federal Diet') is the federal parliament of Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] It is the only constitutional body in the country directly elected by the German people.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag was established by Title III of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany (*Grundgesetz*) in 1949 as one of the legislative bodies of Germany, the other being the Bundesrat.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The members of the Bundestag are representatives of the German people as a whole, are not bound by any orders or instructions and are only accountable to their conscience.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Since the current 21st legislative period, the Bundestag has a fixed number of 630 members.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag is elected every four years by German citizens aged 18 and older.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Elections use a mixed-member proportional representation system which combines first-past-the-post voting for constituency-seats with proportional representation to ensure its composition mirrors the national popular vote.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The German Bundestag cannot dissolve itself; only the president of Germany can do so under certain conditions.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of government at the federal level.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag is considerably more powerful than the Bundesrat, which represents the state governments.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] All bills must first be passed in the Bundestag before they are discussed in the Bundesrat.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundesrat can only accept laws passed by the Bundestag without amendment.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Only in some areas, where laws directly affect the states, can the Bundesrat reject laws; otherwise, it can only lodge an objection to them, which the Bundestag can overrule.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Above all, however, the chancellor and the federal government are solely responsible to the Bundestag.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag also has sole budgetary authority.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Since 1999, the Bundestag has met in the Reichstag building in Berlin.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag also operates in multiple new government buildings in Berlin around the neo-renaissance house and has its own police force (the *Bundestagspolizei*), directly subordinated to the Bundestag Presidency.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag's presiding officer is the president of the Bundestag; they are deputized by the Vice Presidents of the Bundestag.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Since 2025, Julia Klöckner of the CDU/CSU is the president of the Bundestag.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In the protocol order of the federation, the President of the Bundestag ranks second after the President and before the Chancellor.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The first body to be called Bundestag was the legislative body of the German Confederation, which convened in Frankfurt am Main from 1816 to 1866.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] This Bundestag was a convention of state envoys.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] During the revolution of 1848/49, the National Assembly, which met in Frankfurt am Main, was the first elected German parliament and served as a constituent assembly for a German state, which ultimately did not come to pass.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The North German Confederation, founded in 1866/67, was the first German nation state with an established elected parliament, however this ended up being called the Reichstag.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In 1870/71, the federation was expanded to include the southern German territories and was henceforth called the German Empire.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Reichstag building, where the current Bundestag meets since 1999 (see below), was built in 1888.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The German Empire was not yet a parliamentary democracy in the modern sense, but a constitutional monarchy with democratic elements.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Reichstag had to approve all bills, had the right to initiate legislation and, in particular, had budgetary sovereignty.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] However, the Chancellor and the imperial government were not responsible to parliament, but to the emperor alone.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] It was not until 1918, a few weeks before the end of the First World War, that the Reichstag was given the right, as part of a constitutional reform, to withdraw its confidence in the Chancellor and thus force him to resign.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] There was also no universal suffrage for the Reichstag; only men over the age of 25 were entitled to vote in Reichstag elections.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] After its defeat in the First World War, Germany became a republic and a parliamentary democracy with the Weimar Constitution of 1919.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The voting age was lowered to 21 years and women were given the right to vote for (and serve in) the Reichstag.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] However, the first German democracy failed for various reasons, some of which were directly related to the Reichstag.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The pure proportional representation system in elections did not produce clear majorities and the various parties were not sufficiently willing to compromise to form stable governments.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] This led to numerous changes of government and snap elections.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In the last years of the Weimar Republic, opposition parties on the far-right and the far-left held the majority of seats in the Reichstag, which led the governments to rule largely by emergency decrees and bypass parliament.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In 1933, Adolf Hitler was appointed chancellor and through the Reichstag Fire Decree, the Enabling Act of 1933 and the death of President Paul von Hindenburg in 1934, gained unlimited power.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] After this, the Reichstag, in which only the Nazi Party was represented from November 1933 on, met only rarely, above all to extend the emergency laws on which the Nazi dictatorship was formally based.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] With the Basic Law of 1949, Germany's second democratic constitution, the Bundestag was established as the new parliament.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Due to the division of Germany, the Bundestag was de facto a West German parliament until 1990.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The socialist GDR in East Germany had its own parliament, the Volkskammer, which, however, did not emerge from democratic elections except for its last electoral term in 1990.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Because West Berlin was not officially under the jurisdiction of the Basic Law during the division, the Bundestag met in Bonn in several different buildings, including (provisionally) a former waterworks facility and finally in the Bundeshaus.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In addition, owing to the city's legal status, citizens of West Berlin were unable to vote in elections to the Bundestag, and were instead represented by 22 non-voting delegates chosen by the House of Representatives, the city's legislature.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Since German reunification in 1990, the Bundestag has once again been an all-German parliament.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In 1999, the German parliament moved from Bonn to Berlin and sits once again in the Reichstag building.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of the German political system.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag is one of three constitutional bodies (along with the Bundesrat and the federal government) that have the right of initiative for the legislative process.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In order to introduce a bill in the Bundestag, the support of a faction or of a number of MPs corresponding to at least 5% of all MPs is required.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] All bills (including those introduced by the Bundesrat and the government) are first voted on in the Bundestag (for bills from the Bundesrat and the government, however, an opinion must first be obtained from the other body).
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] A bill is first discussed at first reading, then referred to one or more committees, where it can be amended; the resulting committee version then goes back to the plenary, where it is passed at second and third reading.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Amendments can also be tabled at this stage.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] A simple majority (more yes votes than no votes with no regard to abstentions) is required for normal legislative proposals.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In some very rare cases, the Basic Law requires the so-called chancellor majority (majority of all members of parliament) for simple laws, for example to establish new intermediate and subordinate federal authorities.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Laws amending the Basic Law require a two-thirds majority of all members of the Bundestag.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] A law passed by the Bundestag is passed on to the Bundesrat.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Amendments to the Basic Law and laws that directly affect the states must be passed by the Bundesrat by majority vote (amendments to the Basic Law, again, by a two-thirds majority); all other laws are considered passed if the Bundesrat does not object to them within 14 days.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In no case can the Bundesrat make amendments to a bill.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] If the Bundesrat rejects a bill, the matter is often referred to the so-called mediation committee, a body made up of an equal number of members of the Bundestag and Bundesrat, which attempts to negotiate whether the bill can find the approval of both chambers with certain amendments.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] A version amended in this way must then be passed again by a majority in both chambers in order to become law (in this case the rules of procedure of both chambers provide for an abbreviated legislative procedure).
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In the final step, a law must be signed by the President of Germany (they have a right of veto in theory, but this has been used very rarely in the history of the Federal Republic).
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag has an elective function for a number of offices.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The chancellor is elected by the Bundestag and formally appointed by the president of Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] A chancellor's election is necessary whenever the office of chancellor has fallen vacant.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] This is the case if a newly elected Bundestag meets for the first time, or during legislative periods, if the former chancellor died or resigned.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The chancellor's election is one of the few cases in which a vote in the Bundestag requires a majority of all elected members, not just a majority of those assembled at the time, the so-called *Kanzlermehrheit* ("chancellor majority").
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] As with other elections performed by the Bundestag, the chancellor is elected via secret ballot.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] If the nominee reaches the necessary "chancellor majority", the president appoints him or her and, after that, the president of the Bundestag will administer the oath of office before the assembled house.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] If this nominee is not elected, the right of nomination is transferred onto the Bundestag: Candidates can now be nominated for election, whereby a nomination must be supported by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag can hold any number of ballots in this manner for two weeks.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] To be elected, a candidate still needs a "chancellor majority" of yes-votes ("Second voting phase").
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] If the Bundestag is unable to elect a chancellor in these fourteen days, a final ballot is held on the very next day.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Once again, candidates can be nominated by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Candidates receiving a "chancellor majority" in this ballot are elected.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Otherwise, it is up to the President of Germany either to appoint the candidate with the plurality of votes as Chancellor or to dissolve the Bundestag and call new elections ("Third voting phase").
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Another possibility to vote a new chancellor into office is the constructive vote of no confidence, which allows the Bundestag to replace a sitting chancellor, if it elects a new chancellor with the "chancellor-majority".
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag shares responsibility with the Bundesrat for electing the judges of the Federal Constitutional Court.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Both chambers elect four judges to each of the court's two senates.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] They also elect the president and vice-president of the Federal Constitutional Court in alternating order.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In the Bundestag, this requires a two-thirds majority of members present, which has equal at least a majority of all members.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The majority ratios in the Bundestag therefore do not necessarily have to correspond to those in the Federal Assembly.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag is elected for four years, and new elections must be held no earlier than 46 and no later than 48 months after the beginning of a given legislative term.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] By way of exception, there may be an early election if the President of Germany dissolves the Bundestag.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] However, the President only has the right to do so in the event of a failed chancellor election or if an incumbent chancellor requests dissolution after losing a vote of confidence.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The possibility of an early election is therefore in theory much more limited than is the case in some other parliamentary democracies.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] This restriction is intended to encourage the parliamentary groups to cooperate in difficult situations, and is a lesson learned from the experience of the Weimar Republic, in which snap elections were very frequent because the parties were unable to compromise and form stable governments.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] A legislative term ends at the moment when a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for the first time, which must occur within 30 days after an election.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The principle applies that there can be no "period without parliament".
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] An elected Bundestag is fully competent to act until a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for its first session.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Prorogations and dissolutions (in the strict sense), as known in the Westminster system, do not exist in Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Even an early dissolution of the Bundestag, as described above, in practice only leads to an early election, but does not end the legislative period itself.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Following the tradition of German parliamentarism, the Bundestag is subject to the *principle of discontinuation*, meaning that a newly-elected Bundestag is legally regarded as a body and entity completely different from the previous Bundestag.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] This leads to the result that any motion, application or action submitted to the previous Bundestag, e.g. a bill referred to the Bundestag by the Federal Government, is regarded as void by non-decision (German terminology: "*Die Sache fällt der Diskontinuität anheim*").
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Thus any bill that has not been decided upon by the beginning of the new electoral period must be brought up by the government again if it aims to uphold the motion, this procedure in effect delaying the passage of the bill.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Furthermore, any newly-elected Bundestag will have to freshly decide on the rules of procedure (*Geschäftsordnung*), which is done by a formal decision of taking over such rules from the preceding Bundestag by reference.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] If the succeeding Bundestag convenes with same or similar majorities like its predecessor, the parliament can decide to take over earlier initiatives of legislation in the same fashion to abbreviate the process, thus effectively breaking the principle of discontinuation by a pull.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Before an electoral reform in 2023, the Bundestag nominally had 598 members, with the mixture of majority and proportional representation regularly leading to a large number of additional overhang and compensation mandates.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Every elector has two votes: a constituency vote (first vote) and a party list vote (second vote).
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Based solely on the first votes, 299 members are elected in single-member constituencies by first-past-the-post voting.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The second votes are used to produce proportionality with respect to the total number of 630 seats; first at the federal level and then at state level (using the Sainte-Laguë method).
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In most cases, the number of constituencies won by a party in a given state does not exactly correspond to the number of seats to which the party is entitled in that state via second votes.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] To qualify for any seats, however, a party must either win three single-member constituencies via first votes (basic mandate clause) or exceed a threshold of 5% of the second votes nationwide.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] This does not apply to independent constituency candidates: these always enter the Bundestag if they win their constituency.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] (However, no independent constituency candidate has won a constituency since 1949).
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Seats allocated in this way are subtracted from the base number of 630 when the mandates are distributed among the parties.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In addition, the second votes of voters who have elected a successful independent candidate in a constituency are not taken into account when calculating the number of mandates (although they are for the 5% threshold).
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Parties representing recognized national minorities (currently Danes, Frisians, Sorbs, and Romani people) are exempt from both the 5% national threshold and the basic mandate clause.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The only party that has been able to benefit from this provision so far at the federal level is the South Schleswig Voters' Association, which represents the minorities of Danes and Frisians in Schleswig-Holstein, and succeeded in winning a seat in 1949, 2021, and 2025.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] If a member of parliament leaves the Bundestag during the current legislative term, either through resignation or death, another candidate from that party from the corresponding state takes their place.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Successful constituency candidates who did not receive a seat in the previous election due to the principle of second vote coverage are considered first, followed by the candidates on the respective state list.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] However, if the list is exhausted, the seat in question remains vacant for the remainder of the term.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] If the departing member was an independent constituency candidate, the seat also remains empty.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The latest federal election was held on Sunday, 23 February 2025, to elect the members of the 21st Bundestag.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The executive bodies of the Bundestag are the Presidium and the Council of Elders.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Presidium consists of the President, the presiding officer, and several Vice Presidents.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The President and Vice Presidents are elected by the plenary of the Bundestag, whereby traditionally the largest fraction nominates the President and each fraction may nominate a vice president.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In addition to the members of the Presidium, the Council of Elders includes 23 other deputies who are delegated proportionally by the factions.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The council is the coordination hub, determining the daily legislative agenda and assigning committee chairpersons based on Parliamentary group representation.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The council also serves as an important forum for interparty negotiations on specific legislation and procedural issues.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Presidium is responsible for the routine administration of the Bundestag, including its clerical and research activities.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag cannot be adjourned or prorogued during the current legislative term, but is always fully capable of acting and sets its own legislative calendar.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Normally, the Bundestag sits for at least twenty weeks per year, interrupted by non-sessional weeks, especially a long parliamentary summer recess, during which the MPs are present in their constituencies.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The course of a session week is traditionally always the same: meetings of the parliamentary faction's internal committees take place on Monday and Tuesday mornings, and meetings in the faction-plenary on Tuesday afternoon.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] From Wednesday to Friday, plenary sessions and committee meetings take place in parallel (this is the reason why often very few members are present at plenary debates).
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Committee meetings are interrupted on very important items on the agenda so that all MPs have the opportunity to be present in the plenary hall.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The highlights of the procedures include government statements by the Chancellor and the general debate at the beginning of the annual budget deliberations, during which there is a direct clash between the Chancellor and the opposition leader.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Independently of the usual procedure, the Bundestag can also convene for extraordinary sessions at any time.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] This must happen if one third of the MPs, the President of Germany or the Chancellor request it (Basic Law, Article 39.3).
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The most important organisational structures within the Bundestag are 'factions' (*Fraktionen*; sing.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] A parliamentary faction must consist of at least 5% of all members of parliament.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Members of parliament from different parties may only join in a faction if those parties did not run against each other in any German state during the election.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Normally, all parties that surpassed the 5%-threshold build a faction of their own.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The CDU and CSU however, have always formed a joint faction, called CDU/CSU or Union.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] This is possible, as the CSU only runs in the state of Bavaria and the CDU only runs in the other 15 states.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The size of a faction determines the extent of its representation on committees, the time slots allotted for speaking, the number of committee chairs it can hold, and its representation in executive bodies of the Bundestag.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The factions, not the members, receive the bulk of government funding for legislative and administrative activities.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The leadership of each *Fraktion* consists of a parliamentary party leader, several deputy leaders, and an executive committee.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The leadership's major responsibilities are to represent the *Fraktion*, enforce party discipline and orchestrate the party's parliamentary activities.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The members of each *Fraktion* are distributed among working groups focused on specific policy-related topics such as social policy, economics, and foreign policy.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The *Fraktion* meets every Tuesday afternoon in the weeks in which the Bundestag is in session to consider legislation before the Bundestag and formulate the party's position on it.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Parties that do not hold 5% of the Bundestag-seats may be granted the status of a *group* in the Bundestag; this is decided case by case, as the rules of procedure do not state a fixed number of seats for this.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] This status entails some privileges which are in general less than those of a faction.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Most of the legislative work in the Bundestag is the product of standing committees, which exist largely unchanged throughout one legislative period.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The number of committees approximates the number of federal ministries, and the titles of each are roughly similar (e.g., defense, agriculture, and labor).
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] There are, as of the current nineteenth Bundestag, 24 standing committees.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The distribution of committee chairs and the membership of each committee reflect the relative strength of the various Parliamentary groups in the chamber.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] In the current nineteenth Bundestag, the CDU/CSU chaired ten committees, the SPD five, the AfD and the FDP three each, The Left and the Greens two each.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Members of the opposition party can chair a significant number of standing committees (e.g. the Budget Committee of the Bundestag was by tradition chaired by the biggest opposition party, until the 21st Bundestag, when Alternative for Germany was denied this post).
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] These committees have either a small staff or no staff at all.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The members of Bundestag and the presidium are supported by the Bundestag Administration.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] It is headed by the Director, that reports to the President of the Bundestag.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag Administrations four departments are Parliament Service, Research, Information / Documentation and Central Affairs.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag Administration employs around 3,000 employees.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Also following the tradition of German diets, the German Bundestag can legally convene on any location, domestic and foreign.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Reichstag plenary chamber is not determined by law as the location of the assembly, making it a facility of convenience.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Bundestag's predecessor, the German Reichstag, convened in the Kroll Opera House in Berlin, after the Reichstag with its then wooden interior and walls burned down in the Reichstag fire.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] After World War II, the Bundestag did not have own facilities to call home and had to convene in the Bundeshaus in Bonn together with the Bundesrat.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] 1953, the plenary chambers in the Bundeshaus had to be expanded and the Bundestag assembled in a radio building in Cologne.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Until 1965, the Bundestag assembled in West Berlin for nine sessions.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Seven sessions have been held in the Technische Universität Berlin and two sessions in Berlin's Congress Hall in Tiergarten.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The assemblies met severe protest from the communist side, the last session even interrupted by Soviet aircraft in supersonic low-altitude flight.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] 1971, the four occupying powers agreed to not accept Bundestag assemblies in West Berlin anymore.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag assembled in the Old Waterworks Building in Bonn when the old plenary chamber had to get broken down, and in the new plenary chamber for only a few years after Germany's reunification.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The most distinctive assembly of the Bundestag outside its regular chambers was on 4 October 1990, the day after German reunification.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] The Bundestag assembled inside the Reichstag building in Berlin for the first time after 57 years, and remote from its then-regular home in Bonn.
[src:angela-stachowa/deutscher-bundestag] Soon after this most memorable assembly, the Bundestag decided to move from Bonn back to Berlin by a law which sets only the city of Berlin to be the home of the Bundestag, not the building.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] The Sorbian word *Domowina* is a poetic expression for 'homeland'.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] The name was proposed by Domowina co-founder Bogumił Šwjela, then Lutheran pastor of Nochten and Sorbian linguist.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] The Domowina institution, founded in Hoyerswerda in 1912, is situated in Bautzen (Budyšin) in Saxony alongside other cultural institutions of the Sorbian people for which it serves as an umbrella organization.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] The Domowina was closed by Nazi authorities in 1937 and reopened on 10 May 1945, right after the end of World War II, and regained official status in the German Democratic Republic.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] Under East German rule, Domowina was a mass organization included in the National Front, and was effectively controlled by the SED.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] Though the government did recognize Sorbs as a linguistic community within the GDR, they were not recognized as a minority, which ran contrary to the demands of the league.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] Upon the fall of communism in East Germany and German reunification, Domowina was reformed yet again on 17 March 1990, this time as an independent organization.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] In Sorbian, the regional associations are called *župa*.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] founded October 28, 2013 as a successor of the Regional Association Weißwasser and Niesky which in turn was created in 1991 by fusing the two regional associations of Niesky and Weißwasser.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] Those were once one regional association (Niesky, founded 1945), but separated for political reasons in 1957 to match the administrative division of the GDR.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] The Domowina has its main seat in the Serbski dom in Bautzen.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] Domowina's association's journal is *Naša Domowina* ("Our Domowina").
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] Originally, it was created by Pawoł Nedo a supplement for the *Serbske nowiny* newspaper in 1935.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] Today, it bears the full name *Naša Domowina – Informacije třěšneho zwjazka * Informacije kšywowego zwězka * Informationen des Dachverbandes* ("Our Domowina – Information from the umbrella organization") in Upper Sorbian, Lower Sorbian and German.
[src:angela-stachowa/domowina] It is issued by the Bautzen branch office of Domowina.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] Fühmann was the son of an apothecary in Rochlitz an der Iser (Rokytnice nad Jizerou) in the Karkonosze in Czechoslovakia.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] After Volksschule he attended the Jesuitenkonvikt Kalksburg near Vienna for four years, leaving in 1936 to attend the gymnasium in Reichenberg (Liberec), northern Bohemia.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] Fühmann took his *Abitur* exams in Vrchlabí.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] After the annexation of the Sudetenland by Germany, he joined the *Sturmabteilung*.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] Fühmann was drafted into the Wehrmacht in 1941, and was a communications soldier in Greece and the Soviet Union.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] He was captured by Soviet forces in 1945 and sent to a communist rehabilitation school in Noginsk, near Moscow.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] Fühmann returned from Soviet captivity to East Germany, where he lived for the rest of his life in Märkisch Buchholz and Berlin.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] He joined the National Democratic Party of Germany, one of the bloc parties, was active until 1958 and resigned from the party in 1972.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] From 1952 until his death, Fühmann was a freelance writer.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] He mentored young writers, and spoke for those under East German repression.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] In 1976, Fühmann was among the first to sign a letter protesting the exile of Wolf Biermann.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] He received the 1956 Heinrich Mann Prize, the 1957 and 1974 National Prize of East Germany, the 1977 German Critics' Award and the 1982 Geschwister-Scholl-Preis, and was a member of the Academy of Arts, Berlin.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] Fühmann's work includes poems, translations of Czech and Hungarian poems, books for children and young adults, essays, stories, a ballet (*Kirke und Odysseus*) and a collaboration with a photographer (*Was für eine Insel in was für einem Meer*) about the developmentally disabled.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] He also compiled a volume of poems by rearranging parts of a rhyming dictionary and furnishing it with headings.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] Works for children and young people were important to Fühmann throughout his life, and he published his first children's book at the wish of his daughter Barbara.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] Many of Fühmann's early short stories are autobiographical, and in *Das Judenauto* he describes memories of his childhood and youth.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] He later dealt with his involvement in Nazi Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] The concept and the possibility of "change" (in his case, from a supporter of Nazism to a dedicated socialist) were especially important to Fühmann, and play a leading role in *Zweiundzwanzig Tage oder Die Hälfte des Lebens* (one of his major works, a spare diary of a trip to Hungary).
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] In his work, Fühmann emphasized fairly tales, sagas and myths.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] This preoccupation penetrates many of his books, from his children's books to his short stories (*Das Ohr des Dionysios*) and essays.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] With the latter, Fühmann encouraged the publication of authors whose work had rarely appeared in East Germany (such as Georg Trakl and Sigmund Freud).
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] Beginning with *Zweiundzwanzig Tage*, Fühmann increasingly criticized the socialist society of East Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] In a number of letters and later speeches, he attempted to convince East German politicians to change their policies regarding culture.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] This attitude became more visible in his work, especially in *Saiäns-fiktschen*.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] He withdrew from his connections to cultural politics in East Germany, such as the *Schriftstellerverband der DDR* (Writers' Union of East Germany) and the *Akademie der Künste*.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] In later life he began to despair of the political conditions in East Germany (as reflected in his correspondence with Christa Wolf, *Monsieur – wir finden uns wieder*), and was unable to finish his long-planned *magnum opus* (which he called *Bergwerksprojekt* in his letters and notes).
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] It was published posthumously in 1993 as *Im Berg*, with the subtitle (added by himself) *Fragments of a Failure*.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] The Academy of the Arts in Berlin has administered Fühmann's literary estate.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] His library (consisting of about 17,000 volumes, with many notes and underlinings) is part of the *Historische Sammlungen* of the *Zentral- und Landesbibliothek Berlin*.
[src:angela-stachowa/franz-fühmann] His work still interests young artists (such as Barbara Gauger), and the *Franz Fühmann Freundeskreis Märkisch Buchholz* in Berlin illustrates its extent.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The **German National Library** (**DNB**; German: *Deutsche Nationalbibliothek*) is the central archival library and national bibliographic centre for the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] It is one of the largest libraries in the world.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The DNB is also responsible for the *Deutsche Nationalbibliografie* and several special collections like the *Deutsches Exilarchiv 1933–1945* (German Exile Archive), *Anne-Frank-Shoah-Bibliothek* and the *Deutsches Buch- und Schriftmuseum* (German Museum of Books and Writing).
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The German National Library maintains co-operative external relations on a national and international level.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] For example, it is the leading partner in developing and maintaining bibliographic rules and standards in Germany and plays a significant role in the development of international library standards.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The cooperation with publishers has been regulated by law since 1935 for the *Deutsche Bücherei Leipzig* and since 1969 for the *Deutsche Bibliothek Frankfurt am Main*.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Duties are shared between the facilities in Leipzig and Frankfurt, with each center focusing its work in specific specialty areas.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] A third facility has been the *Deutsches Musikarchiv Berlin* (founded 1970), which deals with all music-related archiving (both printed and recorded materials).
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Since 2010, the Deutsches Musikarchiv is also located in Leipzig as an integral part of the facility there.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] During the German revolutions of 1848, various booksellers and publishers offered their works to the Frankfurt Parliament for a parliamentary library.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The library, led by Johann Heinrich Plath, was termed the *Reichsbibliothek* ("Reich library").
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] After the failure of the revolution the library was abandoned and the stock of books already in existence was stored at the Germanisches Nationalmuseum in Nuremberg.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] In 1912, the town of Leipzig, seat of the annual Leipzig Book Fair, the Kingdom of Saxony, and the *Börsenverein der Deutschen Buchhändler* (Association of German booksellers) agreed to found a German National Library in Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Starting 1 January 1913, all publications in German were systematically collected (including books from Austria and Switzerland).
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] In the same year, Gustav Wahl was elected as the first director.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Under Nazi rule, from 1933 to 1945, German libraries were censored, becoming extensions of National Socialist rule.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Books that Nazis seized in occupied countries entered German collections.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] In 1946, Georg Kurt Schauer, Heinrich Cobet, Vittorio Klostermann and Hanns Wilhelm Eppelsheimer, director of the Frankfurt University Library, initiated the re-establishment of a German archive library based in Frankfurt.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The Federal state representatives of the book trade in the American zone agreed to the proposal.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The city of Frankfurt agreed to support the planned archive library with personnel and financial resources.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The US military government gave its approval.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The Library began its work in the tobacco room of the former Rothschild library, which served the bombed university library as accommodation.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] As a result, there were two libraries in Germany, which assumed the duties and function of a national library for the later German Democratic Republic (GDR/DDR) and the Federal Republic of Germany (FRG/BRD), respectively.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Two national bibliographic catalogues almost identical in content were published annually.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] With the reunification of Germany on 3 October 1990, the *Deutsche Bücherei Leipzig* and the *Deutsche Bibliothek Frankfurt am Main* were merged into a new institution, The German Library (*Die Deutsche Bibliothek*).
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The "Law regarding the German National Library" came into force on 29 June 2006.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The law reconfirmed support for the national legal deposit at this library and expanded the collection brief to include online publications set the course for collecting, cataloguing and storing such publications as part of Germany's cultural heritage.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The Library's highest management body, the Administrative Council, was expanded to include two MPs from the Bundestag.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The law also changed the name of the library and its buildings in Leipzig, Frankfurt am Main and Berlin to "*Deutsche Nationalbibliothek*" (German National Library).
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] In July 2000, the DMA also assumed the role as repository for GEMA, Gesellschaft für musikalische Aufführungs- und mechanische Vervielfältigungsrechte, a German music copyright organization.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Since then, music publishers only have to submit copies to DMA, which covers both national archiving and copyright registration.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The 210,000 works of printed music previously held by GEMA were transferred to DMA.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] One of the special activities of the German National Library involves the collection and processing of printed and non-printed documents of German-speaking emigrants and exiles during the period from 1933 to 1945.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The German National Library maintains two exile collections: the Collection of Exile Literature 1933–1945 of the German National Library in Leipzig and the German Exile Archive 1933–1945 of the German National Library in Frankfurt am Main.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Both collections contain printed works written or published abroad by German-speaking emigrants as well as leaflets, brochures and other materials produced entirely or in part by German-speaking exiles.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] In 1998 the German National Library and the German Research Foundation began a publicly funded project to digitise the "Jewish Periodicals in Nazi Germany" collection of approximately 30,000 pages, which were originally published between 1933 and 1943.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Additionally included in the project were 30 German-language emigrant publications "German-language exile journals 1933–1945", consisting of around 100,000 pages.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] These collections were put online in 2004 and were some of the most frequently visited sites of the German National Library.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] In June 2012 the German National Library discontinued access to both collections on its website for legal reasons.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The digitised versions are since then available for use in the reading rooms of the German National Library in Leipzig and Frankfurt am Main only, which caused partly harsh criticism.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The Jewish German-language newspaper haGalil called the libraries action "overzealous".
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Yves Kugelmann, the head of Jüdische Medien AG in Zürich, which owns the rights to Aufbau magazine, one of the Exile Archive's offerings, called the action "completely absurd, confusing, and without merit".
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Anne Lipp of the German Research Foundation concluded that "all projects of the foundation", which have been paid for by public funding and with the intent of publishing online, "must be made public".
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Asmus admits that there was not one single complaint of copyright violation.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Meanwhile, other German and international institutions such as Compact Memory, the Leo Baeck Institute and archive.org have no such compunctions and have begun restoring many of the deleted periodicals to the internet again.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The German National Library only collects German imprints from 1913 onward.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Because of German's history of numerous kingdoms, creating a unified collection of all printed materials produced in Germany is a challenge.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Therefore, the National Library is collaborating with five other libraries who possess large collections in order to coordinate and develop a complete collection of all literature published in German-speaking countries, starting with the year 1400.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] This group is called the *Arbeitsgemeinschaft Sammlung Deutscher Drucke* (AG SDD, Working Group for the Collection of German Imprints).
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The Deutsches Musikarchiv (DMA, German Music Archive) is the central collection of printed and recorded music and the music-bibliographic information centre for Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] It is a Federal agency founded in 1970, tasked with collecting all music published in the country.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Its precursor was the *Deutsche Musik-Phonothek* (1961–1969).
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The DMA moved to Leipzig in 2010, to be housed in an extension of the Deutsche Nationalbibliothek.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Construction work began in 2006 and was completed in 2009.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Formerly situated in Berlin-Lankwitz, the DMA constitutes a department of the German National Library (Deutsche Nationalbibliothek).
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Publishers of printed and recorded music in Germany are required by law (since 1973) to deliver two copies of every edition to the archive.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] One copy is kept at the DMA in Leipzig, the second is deposited in Frankfurt.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The German Museum of Books and Writing (*Deutsches Buch- und Schriftmuseum*) is now hosted at the building in Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Founded in 1884 as the Deutsches Buchgewerbemuseum (German Book Trade Museum) it eventually made its way to the Deutsche Bücherei Leipzig in December 1925.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] It is the world's oldest museum of book culture and addresses both experts and the general public.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] With over one million items in the collection, it is one of the most extensive in the world.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] They offer a wide variety of services including physical and virtual exhibitions, guided tours, seminars and workshops.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The main building of the German National Library in Leipzig was built 1914–1916 after plans of the architect Oskar Pusch.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The facade is 160 m long and faces the "Deutscher Platz" (German Plaza).
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The building was opened on 19 October 1916.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The site of the library (near to today's Alte Messe) had been donated by the city of Leipzig, while Friedrich August III, King of Saxony provided the funds for the building.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] On the facade, the portraits of Otto von Bismarck, Johann Wolfgang von Goethe and Johannes Gutenberg are displayed.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Statues represent Technology, Justice, Philosophy, Medicine etc.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The central reading room contains a picture by Ludwig von Hofmann, depicting Arcadia in Art Nouveau-style.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The staircase displays a mural showing the founders of the German library.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The Library also contains the German Museum of Books and Writing.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The fourth expansion of the library began in 2007 and was opened to the public on 9 May 2011.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Designed by Gabriele Glockler, whose concept for the building was "Cover.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Content." it connects all sections of the building together for the first time.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] The current building of the Frankfurt branch was officially inaugurated on 14 May 1997.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Stuttgart architects Arat-Kaiser-Kaiser were commissioned to design the building after winning an architectural competition in 1984.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Planning was delayed however and construction didn't begin until 1992.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] With an appearance dominated by four main materials: exposed concrete, steel, glass and light Canadian Maple, it features over 300 workstations across three floors, with a large window providing illumination to all of them.
[src:angela-stachowa/german-national-library] Additional storage is located in three levels of underground storage expected to contain enough space until 2045.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig has been a trade city since at least the time of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Via Regia and the Via Imperii, two important medieval trade routes, intersected here, marking the city's economic importance.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The Leipzig Trade Fair dates back to 1190.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Between 1764 and 1945, the city was a centre of publishing.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] After the Second World War, Leipzig remained a major urban centre in East Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Events in Leipzig in 1989 played a significant role in precipitating the fall of Communism in Europe, mainly through demonstrations starting from St.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Since the early 2000s, Leipzig has experienced substantial transformation, marked by urban and economic revitalisation as well as the modernisation of its transport infrastructure.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig is home to one of the oldest universities in Europe (Leipzig University).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] It is the main seat of the German National Library, and the seat of the German Music Archive and the German Federal Administrative Court.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig Zoo is one of the most modern zoos in Europe and as of 2018 ranks first in Germany and second in Europe.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig's late-19th-century Gründerzeit architecture consists of around 12,500 buildings.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The city's central railway terminus Leipzig Hauptbahnhof is Europe's largest railway station measured by floor area.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Since Leipzig City Tunnel came into operation in 2013, it has formed the centrepiece of the S-Bahn Mitteldeutschland (*S-Bahn Central Germany*) public transit system, Germany's largest S-Bahn network.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig has long been a major centre for music, including classical and modern dark wave.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Thomas Choir of Leipzig), a boys' choir, was founded in 1212.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The Leipzig Gewandhaus Orchestra, established in 1743, is one of the oldest symphony orchestras in the world.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Several well-known composers lived and worked in Leipzig, including Johann Sebastian Bach, Felix Mendelssohn, and Richard Wagner.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The University of Music and Theatre "Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy" was founded in 1843.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The Oper Leipzig, one of the most prominent opera houses in Germany, was founded in 1693.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] During a stay in Gohlis, which is now part of the city, Friedrich Schiller wrote his poem "Ode to Joy".
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] A once common English spelling of the city's name was ***Leipsic***, among many variants.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The Latin name ***Lipsia*** was also used in many languages and in the academic publications of the city's university.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The name *Leipzig* is commonly held to derive from *lipa*, the common Slavic designation for linden trees, making the city's name etymologically related to Lipetsk, Russia.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Based on medieval attestations like *Lipzk* (c.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] 1190), the original Slavic name of the city has been reconstructed as **Lipьsko*, which is also reflected in similar forms in neighbouring modern Slavic languages (Sorbian/Polish *Lipsk*, Czech *Lipsko*).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] This has, however, been questioned by more recent onomastic research based on the very oldest forms like *Libzi* (c.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The archaic Romanian name of Leipzig, *Lipsca*, is also derived from a Slavic form.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Lipscani, a historical district in the center of Bucharest, is named after it.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Due to the etymology mentioned above, *Lindenstadt* or *Stadt der Linden* (City of Linden Trees) are common poetic epithets for the city.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Another, somewhat old-fashioned epithet is *Pleiß-Athen* (Athens on the Pleiße River), hinting at Leipzig's long academic and literary tradition, as the seat of one of the oldest German universities and a centre of the book trade.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] It is also referred to as "Little Paris" (*Klein-Paris*) after a line from Goethe's *Faust I*, which is partly set in the famous Leipzig restaurant *Auerbachs Keller*.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In 1937 the Nazi government awarded the city the epithet **Reichsmessestadt Leipzig** (Reich Trade Fair City Leipzig).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In 1989 Leipzig was dubbed a Hero City (*Heldenstadt*), a title that the Soviet Union awarded to some of its cities for their key role in World War II.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In Leipzig's case, though, this was an informal allusion to its role in the fall of the East German regime (through the Monday demonstrations).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] More recently, the city has sometimes been nicknamed *Hypezig*, the "Boomtown of eastern Germany", or "The better Berlin" (*Das bessere Berlin*) and is celebrated by the media as a hip urban centre for its vibrant lifestyle and creative scene with many startups.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig is located in the Leipzig Bay, the southernmost part of the North German Plain, which is the part of the North European Plain in Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The city sits on the White Elster, a river that rises in the Czech Republic and flows into the Saale south of Halle.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The Pleiße and the Parthe join the White Elster in Leipzig, and the large inland delta-like landscape the three rivers form is called *Leipziger Gewässerknoten*.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The site is characterized by swampy areas such as the Leipzig Riparian Forest (*Leipziger Auenwald*), though there are also some limestone areas to the north of the city.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The landscape is mostly flat, though there is also some evidence of moraine and drumlins.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Although there are some forest parks within the city limits, the area surrounding Leipzig is relatively unforested.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] During the 20th century, there were several open-pit mines in the region, many of which have been converted to lakes.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig is also situated at the intersection of the ancient roads known as the Via Regia (King's highway), which traversed Germany in an east–west direction, and the Via Imperii (Imperial highway), a north–south road.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig was a walled city in the Middle Ages and the current "ring" road around the historic centre of the city follows the line of the old city walls.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Since 1992 Leipzig has been divided administratively into ten *Stadtbezirke* (boroughs), which in turn contain a total of 63 *Ortsteile* (localities).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Some of these correspond to outlying villages which have been annexed by Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Like many cities in Eastern Germany, Leipzig has an oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*), with significant continental influences due to its inland location.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Winters are cold, with an average temperature of around 1 °C (34 °F).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Summers are generally warm, averaging at 19 °C (66 °F) with daytime temperatures of 24 °C (75 °F).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Precipitation in winter is about half that of the summer.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The amount of sunshine differs significantly between winter and summer, with an average of around 51 hours of sunshine in December (1.7 hours per day) compared with 229 hours of sunshine in July (7.4 hours per day).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig was first documented in 1015 in the chronicles of Bishop Thietmar of Merseburg as **urbs Libzi** (*Chronicon*, VII, 25) and endowed with city and market privileges in 1165 by Otto the Rich.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig Trade Fair, started in the Middle Ages, has become an event of international importance and is the oldest surviving trade fair in the world.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] This encouraged the growth of the Leipzig merchant bourgeoisie.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] There are records of commercial fishing operations on the river Pleiße that, most likely, refer to Leipzig dating back to 1305, when the Margrave Dietrich the Younger granted the fishing rights to the church and convent of St Thomas.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] There were a number of monasteries in and around the city, including a Franciscan monastery after which the Barfußgäßchen (Barefoot Alley) is named and a monastery of Irish monks (*Jacobskirche*, destroyed in 1544) near the present day *Ranstädter Steinweg* (the old **Via Regia**).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The University of Leipzig was founded in 1409 and Leipzig developed into an important centre of German law and of the publishing industry in Germany, resulting, in the 19th and 20th centuries, with the Reichsgericht (Imperial Court of Justice) and the German National Library being located here.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] During the Thirty Years' War, two battles took place in *Breitenfeld*, about 8 km (5 mi) outside Leipzig city walls.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The first Battle of Breitenfeld took place in 1631 and the second in 1642.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Both battles resulted in victories for the Swedish-led side.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] On 24 December 1701, when Franz Conrad Romanus was mayor, an oil-fueled street lighting system was introduced.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The city employed light guards who had to follow a specific schedule to ensure the punctual lighting of the 700 lanterns.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The Leipzig region was the arena of the 1813 Battle of Leipzig between Napoleonic France and an allied coalition of Prussia, Russia, Austria, and Sweden.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] It was the largest battle in Europe before the First World War and the coalition victory ended Napoleon's presence in Germany and would ultimately lead to his first exile on Elba.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The Monument to the Battle of the Nations celebrating the centenary of this event was completed in 1913.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In addition to stimulating German nationalism, the war had a major impact in mobilizing a civic spirit in numerous volunteer activities.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Many volunteer militias and civic associations were formed, and collaborated with churches and the press to support local and state militias, patriotic wartime mobilization, humanitarian relief and postwar commemorative practices and rituals.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] While over half of the Kingdom of Saxony was formally ceded to Prussia, Leipzig remained part of King Frederick Augustus I.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] When it was made a terminus of the first German long-distance railway to Dresden (the capital of Saxony) in 1839, Leipzig became a hub of Central European railway traffic, with Leipzig Hauptbahnhof the largest terminal station by area in Europe.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The railway station has two grand entrance halls, the eastern one for the Royal Saxon State Railways and the western one for the Prussian state railways.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In the 19th century, Leipzig was a centre of the German and Saxon liberal movements.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The first German labor party, the General German Workers' Association (*Allgemeiner Deutscher Arbeiterverein*, ADAV) was founded in Leipzig on 23 May 1863 by Ferdinand Lassalle; about 600 workers from across Germany travelled to the foundation on the new railway.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig expanded rapidly to more than 700,000 inhabitants.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Huge *Gründerzeit* areas were built, which mostly survived both war and post-war demolition.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] With the opening of a fifth production hall in 1907, the Leipziger Baumwollspinnerei became the largest cotton mill company on the continent, housing over 240,000 spindles.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Yearly production surpassed 5 million kilograms of yarn.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] During World War I, in 1917, the American Consulate was closed, and its building became a temporary place of stay for Americans and Allied refugees from Serbia, Romania, and Japan.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] During the 1930s and 1940s, music was prominent throughout Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Many students attended Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy College of Music and Theatre (then named Landeskonservatorium.) However, in 1944, it was closed due to World War II.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] It re-opened soon after the war ended in 1945.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] On 22 May 1930, Carl Friedrich Goerdeler was elected mayor of Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] He later became an opponent of the Nazi regime.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] He resigned in 1937 when, in his absence, his Nazi deputy ordered the destruction of the city's statue of Felix Mendelssohn.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] On Kristallnacht in 1938, the 1855 Moorish Revival Leipzig synagogue, one of the city's most architecturally significant buildings, was deliberately destroyed.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Goerdeler was later executed by the Nazis on 2 February 1945.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Several thousand forced labourers were stationed in Leipzig during the Second World War.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Beginning in 1933, many Jewish citizens of Leipzig were members of the Gemeinde, a large Jewish religious community spread throughout Germany, Austria, and Switzerland.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In October 1935, the Gemeinde helped found the Lehrhaus (English: a house of study) in Leipzig to provide different forms of studies to Jewish students who were prohibited from attending any institutions in Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Jewish studies were emphasized and much of the Jewish community of Leipzig became involved.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Like all other cities claimed by the Nazis, Leipzig was subject to aryanisation.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Beginning in 1933 and increasing in 1939, Jewish business owners were forced to give up their possessions and stores.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] This eventually intensified to the point where Nazi officials were strong enough to evict the Jews from their own homes.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] They also had the power to force many of the Jews living in the city to sell their houses.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Many people who sold their homes emigrated elsewhere, outside of Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Others moved to Judenhäuser, which were smaller houses that acted as ghettos, housing large groups of people.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The Jews of Leipzig were greatly affected by the Nuremberg Laws.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] However, due to the Leipzig Trade Fair and the international attention it garnered, Leipzig was especially cautious about its public image.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Despite this, the Leipzig authorities were not afraid to strictly apply and enforce anti-semitic measures.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] On 20 December 1937, after the Nazis took control of the city, they renamed it Reichsmessestadt Leipzig, meaning the "Imperial Trade Fair City Leipzig".
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In early 1938, Leipzig saw an increase in Zionism through Jewish citizens.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Many of these Zionists attempted to flee before deportations began.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] On 28 October 1938, Heinrich Himmler ordered the deportation of Polish Jews from Leipzig to Poland.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The Polish Consulate sheltered 1,300 Polish Jews, preventing their deportation.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] On 9 November 1938, as part of Kristallnacht, in Gottschedstrasse, synagogues and businesses were set on fire.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Only a couple of days later, on 11 November 1938, many Jews in the Leipzig area were deported to the Buchenwald Concentration Camp.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] As World War II came to an end, much of Leipzig was destroyed.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Following the war, the Communist Party of Germany provided aid for the reconstruction of the city.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In 1933, a census recorded that over 11,000 Jews were living in Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In the 1939 census, the number had fallen to roughly 4,500, and by January 1942 only 2,000 remained.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In that month, these 2,000 Jews began to be deported.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] On 13 July 1942, 170 Jews were deported from Leipzig to Auschwitz concentration camp.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] On 19 September 1942, 440 Jews were deported from Leipzig to Theresienstadt concentration camp.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] On 18 June 1943, the remaining 18 Jews still in Leipzig were deported from Leipzig to Auschwitz.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] According to records of the two waves of deportations to Auschwitz there were no survivors.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] According to records of the Theresienstadt deportation, only 53 Jews survived.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] During the German invasion of Poland at the start of World War II, in September 1939, the Gestapo carried out arrests of prominent local Poles, and seized the Polish Consulate and its library.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In 1941, the American Consulate was also closed by order of the German authorities.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] During the war, Leipzig was the location of five subcamps of the Buchenwald concentration camp, in which over 8,000 men, women, and children were imprisoned, mostly Polish, Jewish, Soviet, and French, but also Italian, Czech, and Belgian.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Some were rescued by Polish forced laborers of another camp; at least 67 people survived.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] 84 victims were buried on 27 April 1945, however, the total number of victims remains unknown.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] During World War II, Leipzig was repeatedly struck by Allied bombing raids, beginning in 1943 and lasting until 1945.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The first raid occurred on the morning of 4 December 1943, when 442 bombers of the Royal Air Force (RAF) dropped a total amount of almost 1,400 tons of explosives and incendiaries on the city, destroying large parts of the city centre.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] This bombing was the largest up to that time.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Due to the close proximity of many of the buildings hit, a firestorm occurred.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] This prompted firefighters to rush to the city; however, they were unable to control the fires.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Unlike the firebombing of the neighbouring city of Dresden, this was a largely conventional bombing with high explosives rather than incendiaries.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The resultant pattern of loss was a patchwork, rather than wholesale loss of its centre, but was nevertheless extensive.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The Allied ground advance into Germany reached Leipzig in late April 1945.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] 69th Infantry Division fought their way into the city on 18 April and completed its capture after fierce urban action, in which fighting was often house-to-house and block-to-block, on 19 April 1945.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In April 1945, the Mayor of Leipzig, SS-*Gruppenführer* Alfred Freyberg, his wife and daughter, together with Deputy Mayor and City Treasurer Ernest Kurt Lisso, his wife, daughter, and *Volkssturm* Major and former Mayor Walter Dönicke, all committed suicide in Leipzig City Hall.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The United States turned the city over to the Red Army as it pulled back from the line of contact with Soviet forces in July 1945 to the designated occupation zone boundaries.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig became one of the major cities of the German Democratic Republic (East Germany).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Following the end of World War II in 1945, Leipzig saw a slow return of Jews to the city.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] They were joined by large numbers of German refugees who had been expelled from Central and Eastern Europe in accordance with the Potsdam Agreement.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In the mid-20th century, the city's trade fair assumed renewed importance as a point of contact with the Comecon Eastern Europe economic bloc, of which East Germany was a member.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] At this time, trade fairs were held at a site in the south of the city, near the Monument to the Battle of the Nations.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The planned economy of the German Democratic Republic, however, was not kind to Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Before the Second World War, Leipzig had developed a mixture of industry, creative business (notably publishing), and services (including legal services).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] During the period of the German Democratic Republic, services became the concern of the state, concentrated in East Berlin; creative business moved to West Germany; and Leipzig was left only with heavy industry.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] To make matters worse, this industry was extremely polluting, making Leipzig an even less attractive city to live in.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Between 1950 and the end of the German Democratic Republic, the population of Leipzig fell from 600,000 to 500,000.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In October 1989, after prayers for peace at St.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Nicholas Church, established in 1983 as part of the peace movement, the Monday demonstrations started as the most prominent mass protest against the East German government.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The reunification of Germany, however, was at first not good for Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The centrally planned heavy industry that had become the city's specialty was, in terms of the advanced economy of reunited Germany, almost completely unviable, and closed.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Within only six years, 90% of jobs in industry had vanished.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] As unemployment rocketed, the population fell dramatically; some 100,000 people left Leipzig in the ten years after reunification, and vacant and derelict housing became an urgent problem.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Starting in 2000, an ambitious urban-renewal plan first stopped Leipzig's population decline and then reversed it.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The plan focused on saving and improving the city's attractive historic downtown area and particularly its early 20th-century building stock, and attracting new industries, partly through infrastructure improvement.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] However, the renewal has led to gentrification of parts of the city and has not arrested the decline of Leipzig-East.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig is an important economic centre in Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Since the 2010s, the city has been celebrated by the media as a hip urban centre with a very high quality of living.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig is also Germany's fastest growing city.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig was the German candidate for the 2012 Summer Olympics, but was unsuccessful.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] After ten years of construction, the Leipzig City Tunnel opened on 14 December 2013.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig forms the centrepiece of the S-Bahn Mitteldeutschland public transit system, which operates in the four German states of Saxony, Saxony-Anhalt, Thuringia, and Brandenburg.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The first freely elected mayor after German reunification was Hinrich Lehmann-Grube of the Social Democratic Party (SPD), who served from 1990 to 1998.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The mayor was originally chosen by the city council, but since 1994 has been directly elected.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Wolfgang Tiefensee, also of the SDP, served from 1998 until his resignation in 2005 to become federal Minister of Transport.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] He was succeeded by fellow SPD politician Burkhard Jung, who was elected in January 2006 and re-elected in 2013 and 2020.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In the Landtag of Saxony, Leipzig is divided among eight constituencies.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In the Bundestag, Leipzig constitutes two constituencies.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] Leipzig has a population of about 620,000.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In 1930, the population reached its historical peak of over 700,000.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In the 1990s, the population decreased rather rapidly to 437,000 in 1998.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] This reduction was mostly due to outward migration and suburbanisation.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] After almost doubling the city area by incorporation of surrounding towns in 1999, the number stabilised and started to rise again, with an increase of 1,000 in 2000.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] As of 2015, Leipzig is the fastest-growing city in Germany with over 500,000 inhabitants.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The growth of the past 10–15 years has mostly been due to inward migration.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In recent years, inward migration accelerated, reaching an increase of 12,917 in 2014.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] In the years following German reunification, many people of working age took the opportunity to move to the states of the former West Germany to seek employment opportunities.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] This was a contributory factor to falling birth rates.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] However, the number of children born in Leipzig has risen since the late 1990s.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The percentage of the population from an immigrant background is low compared with other German cities.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] As of 2012, only 5.6% of the population were foreigners, compared to the German national average of 7.7%.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p01] The number of people with an immigrant background (immigrants and their children) grew from 49,323 in 2012 to 77,559 in 2016, making them 13.3% of the city's population (Leipzig's population 579,530 in 2016).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In the 2010s, Leipzig was often referred to as *Hypezig*, as overblown comparisons were made to 1990s and early 2000s Berlin.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The affordability, diversity, and openness of the city have attracted many young people from across Europe, leading to a trendsetting alternative atmosphere, resulting in an innovative music, dance, and art scene.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The historic central area of Leipzig features a Renaissance-style ensemble of buildings from the sixteenth century, including the old city hall in the marketplace.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] There are also several baroque period trading houses and former residences of rich merchants.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] As Leipzig grew considerably during the economic boom of the late-nineteenth century, the town has many buildings in the historicist style representative of the *Gründerzeit* era.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Approximately 35% of Leipzig's flats are in buildings of this type.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The new city hall, completed in 1905, is built in the same style.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Some 90,000 apartments in Leipzig were built in *Plattenbau* buildings during Communist rule in East Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Although some of these have been demolished and fewer people live in this type of accommodation in recent years, a significant number still live in Plattenbau apartments.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Grünau, for example, had about 43,600 people living in this sort of accommodation in 2016.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Paul's Church was destroyed by the Communist government in 1968 to make room for a new main building for the university.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] After some debate, the city decided to establish a new, mainly secular building at the same location, called Paulinum, which was completed in 2012.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Its architecture alludes to the look of the former church and it includes space for religious use by the faculty of theology, including the original altar from the old church and two newly built organs.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Many commercial buildings were built in the 1990s as a result of tax breaks after German reunification.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The tallest structure in Leipzig is the chimney of the Stahl- und Hartgusswerk Bösdorf GmbH with a height of 205 m (673 ft).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] With 142 m (466 ft), the tallest building in Leipzig is the City-Hochhaus Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] From 1972 to 1973 it was Germany's tallest building.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] One of the highlights of the city's contemporary arts was the Neo Rauch retrospective opening in April 2010 at the Leipzig Museum of Fine Arts.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] This is a show devoted to the father of the New Leipzig School of artists.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] According to *The New York Times*, this scene "has been the toast of the contemporary art world" for the past decade.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In addition, there are eleven galleries in the so-called Spinnerei.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Grassi Museum complex contains three more of Leipzig's major collections: the Ethnography Museum, Applied Arts Museum, and Musical Instrument Museum (the last of which is run by the University of Leipzig).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The university also runs the Museum of Antiquities.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Founded in March 2015, the G2 Kunsthalle houses the Hildebrand Collection.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] This private collection focuses on the so-called New Leipzig School.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig's first private museum dedicated to contemporary art in Leipzig after the turn of the millennium is located in the city centre close to the famous St.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Thomas Church on the third floor of the former GDR processing centre.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Also dedicated to the contemporary art is the Galerie für Zeitgenössische Kunst Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig is well known for its large parks.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The *Leipziger Auwald* (riparian forest) lies mostly within the city limits.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Neuseenland is an area south of Leipzig where old open-cast mines are being converted into a huge lake district.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Johann Sebastian Bach spent the longest phase of his career in Leipzig, from 1723 until his death in 1750, conducting the Thomanerchor (St.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Nicholas Church, and the Paulinerkirche, the university church of Leipzig (destroyed in 1968).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The composer Richard Wagner was born in Leipzig in 1813, in the Brühl.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Robert Schumann was also active in Leipzig music, having been invited by Felix Mendelssohn when the latter established Germany's first musical conservatoire in the city in 1843.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Gustav Mahler was second conductor (working under Artur Nikisch) at the Leipzig Opera from June 1886 until May 1888, and achieved his first significant recognition while there by completing and publishing Carl Maria von Weber's opera Die Drei Pintos.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Mahler also completed his own 1st Symphony while living in Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Today the conservatory is the University of Music and Theatre Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] A broad range of subjects are taught, including artistic and teacher training in all orchestral instruments, voice, interpretation, coaching, piano chamber music, orchestral conducting, choir conducting, and musical composition in various musical styles.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The drama departments teach acting and scriptwriting.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Bach-Archiv Leipzig, an institution for the documentation and research of the life and work of Bach (and also of the Bach family), was founded in Leipzig in 1950 by Werner Neumann.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Bach-Archiv organizes the prestigious International Johann Sebastian Bach Competition, initiated in 1950 as part of a music festival marking the bicentennial of Bach's death.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The competition is now held every two years in three changing categories.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Bach-Archiv also organizes performances, especially the international festival Bachfest Leipzig and runs the Leipzig Bach Museum.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The city's musical tradition is also reflected in the worldwide fame of the Leipzig Gewandhaus Orchestra, under its chief conductor Andris Nelsons, and the Thomanerchor.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The MDR Leipzig Radio Symphony Orchestra is Leipzig's second largest symphony orchestra.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Its current chief conductor is Kristjan Järvi.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Both the Gewandhausorchester and the MDR Leipzig Radio Symphony Orchestra make use of in the Gewandhaus concert hall.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] For over sixty years Leipzig has been offering a "school concert" programme for children in Germany, with over 140 concerts every year in venues such as the Gewandhaus and over 40,000 children attending.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig is known for its independent music scene and subcultural events.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig has for thirty years been home to the Wave-Gotik-Treffen (WGT), which is currently the world's largest Gothic festival, where thousands of fans of goth music gather in the early summer.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The first Wave Gotik Treffen was held at the Eiskeller club, today known as Conne Island, in the Connewitz district.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Mayhem's notorious album Live in Leipzig was also recorded at the Eiskeller club.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig Pop Up was an annual music trade fair for the independent music scene as well as a music festival taking place on Pentecost weekend.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Its most famous indie-labels are Moon Harbour Recordings (House) and Kann Records (House/Techno/Psychedelic).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Several venues offer live music frequently, including the Moritzbastei, Tonelli's, and Noch Besser Leben.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The cover photo for the Beirut band's 2005 album *Gulag Orkestar*, according to the sleeve notes, was stolen from a Leipzig library by Zach Condon.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The city of Leipzig is also the birthplace of Till Lindemann, best known as the lead vocalist of Rammstein and Bill Kaulitz and Tom Kaulitz, best known as the main members of Tokio Hotel.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] There are more than 300 sport clubs in the city, representing 78 different disciplines.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Over 400 athletic facilities are available to citizens and club members.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The German Football Association (DFB) was founded in Leipzig in 1900.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The city was the venue for the 2006 FIFA World Cup draw, and hosted four first-round matches and one match in the round of 16 in the central stadium.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] VfB Leipzig won the first national Association football championship in 1903.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The club was dissolved in 1946 and the remains reformed as SG Probstheida.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The club was eventually reorganized as football club 1.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] FC Lokomotive Leipzig has had a glorious past in international competition as well, having been champions of the 1965–66 Intertoto Cup, semi-finalists in the 1973–74 UEFA Cup, and runners-up in the 1986–87 European Cup Winners' Cup.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The current Chemie Leipzig from the Leutzsch district, although legally founded in 1997 and started playing in 2008, can trace its roots to the 19th Century.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Chemie Leipzig founded in 1950 dates back to the prewar identity rooted in the establishment of Britannia Leipzig in 1899 and its successor TuRa Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] During the socialist era, the traditions of the club were continued in the East German teams through a complicated history of mergers and name changes before the emergence of FC Sachsen Leipzig in 1990, following German reunification, which continued the clubs traditions.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Red Bull took over a local 5th division football club SSV Markranstädt in May 2009, having previously been denied the right to buy into FC Sachsen Leipzig in 2006.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The club was renamed RB Leipzig and came up through the ranks of German football, winning promotion to the Bundesliga, the highest division of German football in 2016.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The club finished runners-up in its first-ever Bundesliga season and made its debut in the UEFA Champions League in 2017 and the Semi-Final in 2020.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] RB Leipzig won the DFB-Pokal football cup twice, in 2022 and 2023.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Note 1: The RB Leipzig women's football team was formed in 2016 and began play in the 2016–17 season.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Note 2: The club began play in the 2008–09 season.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Since the beginning of the 20th century, ice hockey has gained popularity, and several local clubs established departments dedicated to that sport.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] SC DHfK Leipzig is the men's handball club in Leipzig and were six times (1959, 1960, 1961, 1962, 1965, and 1966) the champion of East Germany handball league and was winner of EHF Champions League in 1966.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] They finally promoted to Handball-Bundesliga as champions of 2.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] They play in the Arena Leipzig which has a capacity of 6,327 spectators in HBL games but can take up to 7,532 spectators for handball in maximum capacity.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Handball-Club Leipzig is one of the most successful women's handball clubs in Germany, winning 21 domestic championships since 1953 and 2 Champions League titles.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The team was however relegated to the third tier league in 2017 due to failing to achieve the economic standard demanded by the league licence.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Leipzig Kings were an American football team playing in the European League of Football (ELF), which is a professional league, that became the first fully professional league in Europe since the demise of NFL Europe.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Kings began by playing games against teams from Germany, Spain, and Poland in June 2021.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] They played their home games at Alfred-Kunze-Sportpark.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Motodrom am Cottaweg is a motorcycle speedway stadium on the west side of the Neue Luppe, located on the Cottaweg road.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The venue is used by the speedway club called Motorsport Club Post Leipzig e.V. and held the East German Speedway Championship in 1978 and a qualifying round of the Speedway World Team Cup in 1991.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] From 1950 to 1990 Leipzig was host of the Deutsche Hochschule für Körperkultur (DHfK, German College of Physical Culture), the national sports college of the GDR.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig also hosted the Fencing World Cup in 2005 and hosts a number of international competitions in a variety of sports each year.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig made a bid to host the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The bid did not make the shortlist after the International Olympic Committee pared the bids down to 5.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Markkleeberger See is a new lake next to Markkleeberg, a suburb on the south side of Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] A former open-pit coal mine, it was flooded in 1999 with groundwater and developed in 2006 as a tourist area.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] On its southeastern shore is Germany's only pump-powered artificial whitewater slalom course, Markkleeberg Canoe Park (Kanupark Markkleeberg), a venue which rivals the Eiskanal in Augsburg for training and international canoe/kayak competition.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig Rugby Club competes in the German Rugby Bundesliga but finished at the bottom of their group in 2013.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig hosted the Indoor Hockey World Cup in 2015.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] All matches were played in Leipzig Arena, with the Netherlands coming out victorious in both the men's and women's tournaments.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] On 1 May every year, the opening of the horse racing season is celebrated in Leipzig's Racecourse Scheibenholz.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig University, founded 1409, is one of Europe's oldest universities.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Karl Bücher, a German economist, founded the *Institut für Zeitungswissenschaften* (Institute for Newspaper Science) at the University of Leipzig in 1916.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] It was the first institute of its kind to be established in Europe, and it marks the commencement of academic study of media communication in Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, a philosopher and mathematician, was born in Leipzig in 1646, and attended the university from 1661 to 1666.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Nobel Prize laureate Werner Heisenberg worked at the university as a physics professor (from 1927 to 1942), as did Nobel Prize laureates Gustav Ludwig Hertz (physics), Wilhelm Ostwald (chemistry), and Theodor Mommsen (Nobel Prize in Literature).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The 2022 Nobel Prize in Physiology and Medicine went to Svante Pääbo, an honorary professor at the university.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Other former university staff include mineralogist Georg Agricola, writer Gotthold Ephraim Lessing, philosopher Ernst Bloch, founder of psychophysics Gustav Theodor Fechner, and founder of modern psychology, Wilhelm Wundt.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The university's notable former students include writers Johann Wolfgang Goethe and Erich Kästner, philosopher Friedrich Nietzsche, political activist Karl Liebknecht, and composer Richard Wagner.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Angela Merkel, former German chancellor, studied physics at Leipzig University.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The university has about 30,000 students.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] A part of Leipzig University is the German Institute for Literature which was founded in 1955 under the name "Johannes R.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Many noted writers have graduated from this school, including Heinz Czechowski, Kurt Drawert, Adolf Endler, Ralph Giordano, Kerstin Hensel, Sarah and Rainer Kirsch, Angela Krauß, Erich Loest, and Fred Wander.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] After its closure in 1990 the institute was refounded in 1995 with new teachers.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Academy of Visual Arts (*Hochschule für Grafik und Buchkunst*) was established in 1764.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Its 600 students (as of 2018) are enrolled in courses in painting and graphics, book design/graphic design, photography and media art.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The school also houses an Institute for Theory.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The University of Music and Theatre offers a broad range of subjects ranging from training in orchestral instruments, voice, interpretation, coaching, piano chamber music, orchestral conducting, choir conducting, and musical composition to acting and scriptwriting.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Leipzig University of Applied Sciences (HTWK) has approximately 6,200 students (as of 2007) and is (as of 2007) the second biggest institution of higher education in Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] It was founded in 1992, merging several older schools.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] As a university of applied sciences (German: *Fachhochschule*) its status is slightly below that of a university, with more emphasis on the practical parts of education.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The HTWK offers many engineering courses, as well as courses in computer science, mathematics, business administration, librarianship, museum studies, and social work.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] It is mainly located in the south of the city.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The private Leipzig Graduate School of Management, (in German *Handelshochschule Leipzig (HHL)*), is the oldest business school in Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] According to The Economist, HHL is one of the best schools in the world, ranked at number six overall.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Branch campus of Lancaster University, it is the first public UK university with a campus in Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Lancaster University Leipzig was founded in 2020 and currently has a diverse international student body with more than 45 nationalities.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig is currently the home of twelve research institutes and the Saxon Academy of Sciences and Humanities.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig is home to one of the world's oldest schools, *Thomasschule zu Leipzig* (St.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Thomas' School, Leipzig), which gained fame for its long association with the Bach family of musicians and composers.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Lutheran Theological Seminary is a seminary of the Evangelical Lutheran Free Church in Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The seminary trains students to become pastors for the Evangelical Lutheran Free Church or for member church bodies of the Confessional Evangelical Lutheran Conference.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The city is a location for automobile manufacturing by BMW and Porsche in large plants north of the city.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In 2011 and 2012 DHL transferred the bulk of its European air operations from Brussels Airport to Leipzig/Halle Airport.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Kirow Ardelt AG, the world market leader in breakdown cranes, is based in Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The city also houses the European Energy Exchange, the leading energy exchange in Central Europe.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] VNG – Verbundnetz Gas AG, one of Germany's large natural gas suppliers, is headquartered at Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In addition, inside its larger metropolitan area, Leipzig has developed an important petrochemical centre.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Some of the largest employers in the area (outside of manufacturing) include software companies such as Spreadshirt and the various schools and universities in and around the Leipzig/Halle region.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The University of Leipzig attracts millions of euros of investment yearly and celebrated its 600th birthday in 2009.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig also benefits from world-leading medical research (Leipzig Heart Centre) and a growing biotechnology industry.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Bio City Leipzig, established in 2003, is a biotechnology business incubator.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Many bars, restaurants, and stores in the downtown area are patronized by German and foreign tourists.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig Main Train Station is the location of a shopping mall.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig is one of Germany's most visited cities with over 3 million overnight stays in 2017.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In 2010, Leipzig was included in the top 10 cities to visit by *The New York Times*, and ranked 39th globally out of 289 cities for innovation in the 4th Innovation Cities Index published by Australian agency 2thinknow.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In 2015, Leipzig have among the 30 largest German cities the third best prospects for the future.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In recent years Leipzig has often been nicknamed the "Boomtown of eastern Germany" or "Hypezig".
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] As of 2013 it had the highest rate of population growth of any German city.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig has a dense network of socio-ecological infrastructures.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In December 2013, according to a study by GfK, Leipzig was ranked as the most livable city in Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In 2015/2016, Leipzig was named by the consumer portal verbraucherzentrale.de as the second-best city for students in Germany (after Munich).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In a 2017 study from the Institut für Handelsforschung Köln, the Leipzig inner city ranked first among all large cities in Germany due to its urban aesthetics, gastronomy, and shopping opportunities.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] According to HWWI/Berenberg-Städteranking, since 2018 it also has the second-best future prospects of all cities in Germany, second to Munich in 2018 and Berlin in 2019.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] According to a 2017 Global Least & Most Stressful Cities Ranking by Zipjet, a London-based online laundry service, Leipzig was one of the least stressful cities in the World.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] It was ranked 25th out of 150 cities worldwide and above Dortmund, Cologne, Frankfurt, and Berlin.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig was named European City of the Year at the 2019 Urbanism Awards.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] According to the 2019 study by Forschungsinstitut Prognos, Leipzig is the most dynamic region in Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Within 15 years, the city climbed 230 places and occupied in 2019 rank 104 of all 401 German regions.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig was listed as one of 52 places to go in 2020 by *The New York Times* and the highest-ranking German destination.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig Hauptbahnhof has been ranked the best railway station in Germany and the third-best in Europe in a consumer organisation poll, surpassed only by St Pancras railway station and Zürich Hauptbahnhof.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Founded at the crossing of Via Regia and Via Imperii, Leipzig has been a major interchange of inter-European traffic and commerce since medieval times.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] After the Reunification of Germany, immense efforts to restore and expand the traffic network have been undertaken and left the city area with an excellent infrastructure.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig/Halle Airport is the international commercial airport of the region.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] It is located at the Schkeuditzer Kreuz junction northwest of Leipzig, halfway between the two major cities.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The easternmost section of the new Erfurt-Leipzig/Halle line under construction gave the airport a long-distance railway station, which was also integrated into the ICE network when the railway line was completed in 2015.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Passenger flights are operated to and from the major German hub airports, European metropolises and holiday destinations, especially to the Mediterranean region and North Africa.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The airport is of international importance in the cargo sector.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In Germany, it ranks second behind Frankfurt am Main, fifth in Europe and 26th worldwide (as of 2011).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] DHL uses the airport as its central European hub.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] It is also the home base of the freight airlines Aerologic and European Air Transport Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The former military airport near Altenburg, Thuringia, called Leipzig–Altenburg Airport, about a half-hour drive from Leipzig, was served by Ryanair until 2010.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Berlin Brandenburg Airport can be reached from Leipzig in one and a half hours by train since December 2025.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Opened in 1915, Leipzig Hauptbahnhof (lit.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] *main station*) is the largest overhead railway station in Europe in terms of its built-up area.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] At the same time, it is an important supra-regional junction in the Intercity-Express (ICE) and Intercity network of the Deutsche Bahn as well as a connection point for S-Bahn and regional traffic in the Halle/Leipzig area.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In Leipzig the Intercity Express routes (Hamburg–)Berlin–Leipzig–Nuremberg–Munich and Dresden–Leipzig–Erfurt–Frankfurt am Main–(Wiesbaden/Saarbrücken) intersect.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig is also the starting point for the intercity lines Leipzig-Halle (Saale)–Magdeburg–Hannover–Dortmund–Köln and –Bremen–Oldenburg(–Norddeich Mole).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Both lines complement each other at hourly intervals and also stop at Leipzig/Halle Airport.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The only international connection is the daily EuroCity Leipzig-Prague.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Most major and medium-sized towns in Saxony and southern Saxony-Anhalt can be reached without changing trains.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] There are also direct connections via regional express lines to Falkenberg/Elster-Cottbus, Hoyerswerda, and Dessau-Magdeburg as well as Chemnitz.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Neighbouring Halle (Saale) can be reached via three S-Bahn lines, two of which run via Leipzig/Halle Airport.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The surrounding area of Leipzig is served by numerous regional and S-Bahn lines.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The city's railway connections are currently being greatly improved by major construction projects, particularly within the framework of the German Unity transport projects.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The line to Berlin has been extended and has been passable at 200 km/h (120 mph) since 2006.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] On 13 December 2015, the high-speed line from Leipzig to Erfurt, designed for 300 km/h (190 mph), was put into operation.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Its continuation to Nuremberg followed in December 2017.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] This integration into the high-speed network considerably reduced the journey times of the ICE from Leipzig to Nuremberg, Munich, and Frankfurt am Main.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Leipzig-Dresden railway line, which was the first German long-distance railway to go into operation in 1839, is also undergoing expansion for 200 km/h.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The most important construction project in regional transport was the four-kilometer-long city tunnel, which went into operation in December 2013 as the main line of the S-Bahn Mitteldeutschland.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] There are freight stations in the districts of Wahren and Engelsdorf.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In addition, a freight traffic centre has been set up near the Schkeuditzer Kreuz junction for goods handling between road and rail, as well as a freight station on the site of the DHL hub at Leipzig/Halle Airport.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig is the core of the S-Bahn Mitteldeutschland line network.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Together with the tram, six of the ten lines form the backbone of local public transport and an important link to the region and the neighbouring Halle.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The main line of the S-Bahn consists of the underground S-Bahn stations Hauptbahnhof, Markt, Wilhelm-Leuschner-Platz, and Bayerischer Bahnhof leading through the City Tunnel as well as the above-ground station Leipzig MDR.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] There are a total of 30 S-Bahn stations in the Leipzig city area.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Endpoints of the S-Bahn lines include Wurzen, Zwickau, Dessau, and Lutherstadt Wittenberg.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Two lines run to Halle, one of them via Leipzig/Halle Airport.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] With the timetable change in December 2004, the networks of Leipzig and Halle were combined to form the Leipzig-Halle S-Bahn.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] However, this network only served as a transitional solution and was replaced by the S-Bahn Mitteldeutschland on 15 December 2013.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] At the same time, the main line tunnel, marketed as the Leipzig City Tunnel, went into operation.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The tunnel, which is almost four kilometres long, crosses the entire city centre from the main railway station to the Bavarian railway station.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The S-Bahn stations are up to 22 metres underground.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] This construction was the first to create a continuous north–south axis, which had not existed until now due to the north-facing terminus station.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The connection to the south of the city and the federal state will thus be greatly improved.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Leipziger Verkehrsbetriebe, existing since 1 January 1917, operate a total of 15 tram lines and 47 bus lines in the city.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The total length of the tram network is 146 km (91 mi), making it the largest in Saxony ahead of Dresden (134.4 km (83.5 mi)) and the second largest in Germany after Berlin (196 km (122 mi)).
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The longest line in the Leipzig network is line 11, which connects Schkeuditz with Markkleeberg over 22 kilometres and is the only tram line in Leipzig to run in three tariff zones of the Central German Transport Association.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Night bus lines N1 to N9 and the night tram N17 operate in the night traffic.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] On Saturdays, Sundays, and holidays the tram line N10 and the bus line N60 also operate.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The central transfer point between the bus and tram lines as well as to the S-Bahn is Leipzig Central Station.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Like most German cities, Leipzig has a traffic layout designed to be bicycle-friendly.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In most of the one-way central streets, cyclists are explicitly allowed to cycle both ways.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] A few cycle paths have been built or declared since 1990.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] According to the data from the 2021/22 traffic count, the Saxons' Bridge has the highest traffic occupancy with over 15,000 cyclists per day in cycling in Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Since 2004 there is a bicycle-sharing system.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Bikes can be borrowed and returned via smartphone app or by telephone.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Since 2018, the system has enabled flexible borrowing and returning of bicycles in the inner city; in this zone, bicycles can be handed in and borrowed from almost any street corner.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Outside these zones, there are stations where the bikes are waiting.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The current locations of the bikes can be seen via the app.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] There are cooperation offers with the Leipzig public transport companies and car sharing in order to offer as complete a mobility chain as possible.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Several federal motorways pass by Leipzig: the A 14 in the north, the A 9 in the west, and the A 38 in the south.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The three motorways form a triangular partial ring of the double ring Mitteldeutsche Schleife around Halle and Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] To the south toward Chemnitz, the A 72 is also partly under construction.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The federal roads B 2, B 6, B 87, B 181, and B 184 lead through the city area.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The ring road (Innenstadtring), which corresponds to the course of the old city fortification, surrounds the city centre of Leipzig, which today is largely traffic-calmed.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig has a dense network of carsharing stations.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Additionally, since 2018 there is also a stationless car sharing system in Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Here the cars can be parked and booked anywhere in the inner city without having to define a specific car or period in advance.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Finding and booking is done via a smartphone app.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Leipzig is one of the few cities in Germany with vehicle for hire services that can be booked via a mobile app.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In contrast to taxicab services, the start and destination must be defined beforehand and other passengers can be taken along at the same time if they share a route.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In March 2018, the Leipzig Long-Distance Bus Terminal opened a few steps outside of the Hauptbahnhof building on its east side.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In addition to a large number of national lines, several international lines also serve Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The cities of Bregenz, Budapest, Milan, Prague, Sofia, and Zurich, among others, can be reached without having to change trains.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Around 30,000 journeys and 1.5 million passengers a year are expected at the new bus station.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Some lines also use Leipzig/Halle Airport, located at the A 9/A 14 motorway junction, and Leipziger Messe for a stop.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Passengers can take the S-Bahn from there to the city centre.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] In the first half of the 20th century, the construction of the Elster-Saale canal, White Elster, and Saale was started in Leipzig in order to connect to the network of waterways.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The outbreak of the Second World War stopped most of the work, though some may have continued through the use of forced labor.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Lindenauer port was almost completed but not yet connected to the Elster-Saale and Karl Heine Canal respectively.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The Leipzig rivers (White Elster, New Luppe, Pleiße, and Parthe) in the city have largely artificial river beds and are supplemented by some channels.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] These waterways are suitable only for small leisure boat traffic.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Through the renovation and reconstruction of existing mill races and watercourses in the south of the city and flooded disused open cast mines, the city's navigable water network is being expanded.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] A link between Karl Heine Canal and the disused Lindenauer port was opened in 2015.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Still more work was scheduled to complete the Elster-Saale canal.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] Such a move would allow small boats to reach the Elbe from Leipzig.
[src:angela-stachowa/leipzig-p02] The intended completion date has been postponed because of an unacceptable cost-benefit ratio.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] The **Luchterhand Literaturverlag** is a German publisher of contemporary literature based in Munich.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] It was founded in 1924, and was acquired by Random House in 2001.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] Luchterhand is considered one of the most prestigious publishers in Germany.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] Publications include literature from Günter Grass and Christa Wolf and many others.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] In 1924, Hermann Karl Wilhelm Luchterhand founded Luchterhand Publisher in Berlin, dedicated to taxation and law.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] He then published an information pamphlet on tax, which added to the earlier publications of forms and manuals for the payroll office.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] In 1934, he appointed Eduard Reifferscheid as managing partner.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] In 1936, Luchterhand went back to his private life.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] The reasons for Hermann Luchterhand's withdrawal are still unknown.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] After the end of World War II, the company's headquarters moved during the reconstruction from Berlin to Neuwied.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] Alfred Andersch, along with many others, participated with his magazine articles and drawings to create an additional literary program.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] The first literary publications appeared in 1954.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] The literary program of Luchterhand has existed since the year 1954.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] The publisher released several works from numerous important authors: such as "Die Vorzüge der Windhühner", the first book by Günter Grass which was followed in 1959 by the novel "The Tin Drum".
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] An important part of the program had up until the 1990s licensed editions from DDR-authors.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] In 1993, the *Luchterhand collection* was sold to dtv Verlagsgesellschaft.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] Luchterhand has works from more than 100 writers available.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] Every year, over twenty new titles appear.
[src:angela-stachowa/luchterhand-literaturverlag] Among the more well-known works from recent years include "Gleis 4" by Franz Hohler, "Das Ungeheuer" Terézia Mora, "Die Erfindung des Lebens" by Hanns-Josef Ortheil and also "Vor dem Fest" by Saša Stanišić.
